Document Title: Code of Conduct Policy – Kahana Inc.
Owner: HR / Legal
Approved By: CEO

1. Purpose
This Code of Conduct sets out the ethical and professional standards expected of everyone who works for or represents Kahana. It exists to protect our people, our customers, and our reputation, and to support compliance with laws and frameworks such as SOC 2.

2. Scope
This policy applies to:

All Kahana employees, contractors, interns, and officers.

All activities performed on behalf of Kahana, whether on‑site, remote, or at customer/vendor locations.

3. Ethical Standards and Professional Behavior
All personnel must:

Act with honesty, integrity, and respect in all business dealings.

Treat colleagues, customers, and partners fairly and without discrimination or harassment.

Follow all applicable laws, regulations, and company policies.

Protect Kahana’s and customers’ assets, including information, systems, and equipment.

Harassment, bullying, discrimination, retaliation, and other abusive or inappropriate behavior are strictly prohibited and may result in disciplinary action, up to and including termination.

4. Conflicts of Interest
A conflict of interest arises when personal interests could improperly influence, or appear to influence, decisions made on behalf of Kahana.

Personnel must:

Avoid situations where personal, financial, or family interests conflict with Kahana’s interests.

Not use their position at Kahana to obtain personal benefits from customers, vendors, or competitors.

Disclose any actual or potential conflicts of interest promptly to their manager, HR, or Legal so they can be reviewed and managed.

Examples include: outside employment that competes with Kahana, personal investments in competitors or critical vendors, or relatives working at key counterparties where you make decisions about them.

5. Confidentiality and Information Security
All non‑public information about Kahana, its customers, and partners must be treated as confidential and handled according to Kahana’s security and data policies.

Personnel must:

Only access and use information needed for their job (“need‑to‑know”).

Not share confidential information outside Kahana unless authorized and under appropriate agreements (e.g., NDA).

Follow security policies (Acceptable Use, Workstation Security, Data Classification, Incident Reporting, etc.).

When posting on LinkedIn or other professional/social platforms, you represent Kahana; maintain professionalism and do not disclose confidential or customer information.

Continue to protect confidential information even after leaving Kahana.

6. Use of Company Assets and Systems
Company assets (devices, software, accounts, networks) must be used responsibly:

Primarily for legitimate business purposes.

In accordance with the Acceptable Use Policy and other IT/security policies.

Without engaging in illegal activities, harassment, or actions that could harm Kahana or its customers.

Unauthorized copying of software, use of unapproved tools for work data, or deliberate circumvention of security controls is prohibited.

7. Anti‑Bribery and Gifts
Personnel must not:

Offer, give, solicit, or accept bribes, kickbacks, or other improper payments to influence business decisions.

Give or receive gifts, hospitality, or favors that could reasonably be seen as creating an obligation or influencing judgment.

Reasonable, customary business courtesies (e.g., low‑value meals, small tokens) may be acceptable if they are modest, lawful, and in line with local norms. When in doubt, employees should consult HR or Legal.

8. Reporting Concerns and Non‑Retaliation
Everyone is responsible for speaking up if they see or suspect:

Violations of this Code of Conduct or other policies.

Fraud, theft, or misuse of assets.

Security or privacy incidents.

Harassment, discrimination, or other misconduct.

Reports can be made to:

Your manager.

HR.

The Security Lead (for security/privacy issues).

Any other designated reporting channel (once established).

Kahana prohibits retaliation against anyone who raises a concern in good faith or participates in an investigation. Retaliation itself is a serious violation of this policy.

9. Compliance and Disciplinary Action
Compliance with this Code of Conduct is a condition of employment or engagement with Kahana.

Violations may result in actions ranging from coaching and written warnings to termination of employment or contract, and, where appropriate, legal action.

The severity of action will depend on the nature of the violation, its impact, and any prior history.

10. Training and Acknowledgment
This Code of Conduct is provided during onboarding and is available in company documentation.

Employees must acknowledge in writing (e.g., e‑signature) that they have read, understood, and agree to comply with this Code and related policies.

Periodic refresher training may be required as part of the Security Awareness Training Program.

11. Review and Updates
This Code of Conduct will be reviewed at least annually, or when there are significant changes in Kahana’s business, laws, or regulatory requirements. Updates will be approved by leadership and communicated to all personnel.


“Code of Conduct” acknowledgment text you can include in offer letters or in your HR system for employees to sign: 
"I acknowledge that I have received, read, and understood Kahana’s Employee Handbook and Code of Conduct, including its security, confidentiality, and acceptable use requirements. I understand that compliance with these policies is a condition of my employment/engagement with Kahana, and I agree to follow them at all times, to protect company and customer information, and to promptly report any suspected violations or security incidents through the channels Kahana provides."